<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><i>Historical Note: Sitting pets used to be the cause of fights
since mobs would see the pet sitting and attack. Now that mobs aren't KOS unless they are already fighting, you can use the sit command without fear of
being attacked for it. (Note: You're still a prime target in the mind of a mob
if you're sitting).</i><br>
&nbsp;<br>
In my opinion, pet taunting was turned down too much when it was
&quot;fixed&quot; in 2001. You will find that many monsters will attack players
and completely ignore the pet. Earth and Air can temporarily immobilize a mob
and are therefore more effective at keeping the mob focused on themselves rather
than on you or your group members.&nbsp; This weak taunt is most noticeable at 
lower levels.</p>
<p><b>Important: </b> Your pet listens to everything you say when it is your target. Be
careful what you say in normal chat mode (pets don't listen to group chat, guild
chat, OOC, shout, etc) when your pet is targeted. Much like the Quest discussion
pointed out earlier, your pet will respond to anything that contains key words.
If you had your pet targeted and you say, &quot;How did Soandso get lost again?
He's a ranger for crying out loud,&quot; your pet will promptly vanish since you
said, &quot;get lost&quot; in the sentence. Smart pet, dumb mage! I've made this
very mistake myself…(it's even worse when you say the word attack and your pet
tries to parse exactly what you told it to attack).</p>

<h3>Pet Strategy</h3>

<p><u>
Buff your pet.</u> At this level, you do not have spells to enhance your pet.
However, others you group with likely will. Your pet will benefit from any
spells cast on it just like a player. If the pet will be tanking mobs, your
healer should check the pet's health periodically. Note: the results of /pet
report health are only seen by you, not the group.</p>

<p><u>Give your pet a weapon</u> as at low levels, most of the weapons you find
are better than your pet's barehanded attack.&nbsp; Your pet does not currently
dual wield, so you should give your pet the best 2H weapon you can afford (or
you can summon).&nbsp; For example, a level 4 pet that hits for 10 points max
will hit for 14 points with a 7 damage staff.&nbsp; That's a 40% improvement!</p>

<p><u>
Assist your pet</u>. You can use /pet report health or target the pet to see how it
is doing. If it is getting too low on health, you can step into the fight and
melee alongside your pet. Since the mob will switch to you when you do this,
your pet can continue doing damage until the fight is finished. A good strategy
is to pull a mob with a spell and then send your pet to attack. You can cast
another spell or two while your pet is fighting. Check the pet's health and
decide if your pet needs you to step in, cast another spell, or is doing just
fine on its own.</p>

<p><u>
Your pet is expendable.</u> If something goes horribly wrong and your pet is going
to die, it is very likely that you are next to be served. If it is hopeless, you
should gate (if you're solo…don't leave a group hanging) before your pet dies.
It's a nice touch to /salute your pet as you are channeling gate. Goodbye little
buddy…thanks for saving my bacon. *sniff* If it is not hopeless, you can start
channeling a new pet before your current one dies. You must be sure that your
existing pet is dead and gone before you summon a new one. Timing is important.
But then, you've got a command that will finish off your current pet instantly…don't
you?</p>

<p><u>
Pet kiting</u> is a tactic that many magicians stumble onto at this level. If you
nuke a mob heavily, it will be very angry at you. You can run away from the mob
and it will chase you. If you have a pet, your pet will chase the mob. The
result of this is that your pet is getting &quot;free&quot; hits on the mob,
which would rather chase you than turn and fight your pet. This requires an
outdoor environment in which there aren't many other mobs that will attack. In
general, other players see kiting as a cheap tactic. Kiting may also endanger
other players. I'm listing it here for the sake of completeness, but you won't
learn much about the game if you spend most of your time this way. Pet kiting it
is a good emergency tactic at this level. If you and your pet are low on health
and you are low on mana, pet kiting may enable you to win the fight. My advice
is to keep it in mind, but use it only as a last resort. Never endanger other
players to save yourself. And, if you do have a train of mobs behind you, it is
proper to give a shout to the zone that you're incoming to ____ with a train.</p>

<p><u>Magical beings</u> are tough to hit.&nbsp; In fact, they're immune to
normal weapons.&nbsp; At this level, you won't likely encounter them, but it's
good to know about them now.&nbsp; Your pet cannot hit a magic creature with its
hands until level 10.&nbsp; However, you can summon a dagger that is
magic.&nbsp; Hand the dagger to pet...your pet will know how to use it.&nbsp; At
this level, you need only hand a single dagger to your pet.</p>

<p><u>Equipping your pet</u> is a good idea.&nbsp; You should give it any armor you
encounter that you don't need and do not intend to sell.&nbsp; Although you
won't see the graphics, your pet will equip the items you give it.&nbsp; You can
give your pet a bit more AC by passing it any armor you'd otherwise
destroy.&nbsp; The benefit is small, so if you need money, you should sell the
armor to NPCs or other players rather than giving it to your pet.&nbsp; Your pet
will not return any items.&nbsp; When your pet dies, there will be no
corpse.&nbsp; Be sure you are handing your pet something you truly do not need.</p>

<p><u>Manage the pet's aggro list.</u>&nbsp; Your pet will attack things that
you tell it to attack (if it can).&nbsp; It will also attack things that attack
it or you.&nbsp; Pets have memories.&nbsp; If they are attacking Mob_01 and you
tell it to attack Mob_02, get attacked by Mob_02 or Mob_02 attacks the pet, your
pet will &quot;hate&quot; Mob_02 and may decide to attack it immediately or wait
until it has finished with Mob_01.&nbsp; If you do not want the pet to switch to
Mob_02, back off the pet (/pet back off) and send it at Mob_01 again.&nbsp;
You'll have to repeat this if Mob_02 attacks you or the pet again.&nbsp; You can
also use the hate list to get your pet to automatically attack Mob_02 when
Mob_01 dies.&nbsp; If you tell your pet to attack Mob_02 while it is fighting
Mob_01, it will attack Mob_02 once Mob_01 dies.&nbsp; Be careful.&nbsp; Your pet
will switch to Mob_02 before Mob_01 dies if Mob_02 makes your pet angry
enough.&nbsp; If that happens, Mob_01 may come for you, or your pet could be
tanking 2 mobs.</p>

<p><i>
Historical Note: Pets used to share in the experience from a mob. Groups and
mages were overly concerned about how much of a share in the experience a pet
took. In my opinion, pets never took more of the experience than they made up
for in power, but that's moot now. As long as you or a member of your group does
1 point of damage to the mob, you will get the full experience. If you let your
pet kill a mob outright -- with not even 1 point of help -- you will get much
less experience.&nbsp; Pets have never benefited from the experience they
&quot;take&quot; from a fight.&nbsp; They do not &quot;ding&quot; from
experience gained while fighting.</i></p>

<p>Historical Note:&nbsp; There used to be some randomness in the level of the pet 
a mage could summon. For example, level 4 pet
spells could summon a pet from level 3 to 6. Since that's a big range 
(especially at this level), mages used to burn a lot more malachite trying to 
get the best pet possible.&nbsp; That's no longer necessary since you always get 
the highest level pet!</p>

<h3>Components</h3>

<p>
Summoning is a specialized spell that requires malachite to work. All pets,
regardless of level, require one piece of malachite to summon. Malachite is
relatively inexpensive and stocked in many cities. I carry anywhere from 20 - 80
malachite on me at a time. If you're tight on cash (as I was at level 4) you
might only carry 5 - 10, just remember than if you run out of malachite, you
can't make pets until you get more.</p>

<p><i>
Historical Note: At level 12 magician pets used to require a different component.
If you see lapis lazuli listed on a website, it's out of date. Lapis is much
more expensive (comparatively) than malachite, so be happy!&nbsp;</i></p>

