<h3>
Fire Flux</h3>

<p>This is your first Point Blank Area of Effect (PBAoE) spell.&nbsp; This spell
sends out a ring of fire from your position.&nbsp; It will never damage you, but
it will burn anything you can legally target for damage.&nbsp; There are not
many times when this type of spell is useful, however if you have a need to kill
several green mobs around you, Fire Flux is for you.&nbsp; Remember...if you
don't kill everything you hit, you're going to have some angry mobs to
placate.&nbsp; Note that this spell is not mana efficient unless you are casting
it on multiple targets.</p>

<p>
<b>Important:</b> Do not use any AoE spell like Fire Flux around NPCs you'd rather not
fight. As a level 4, I tested my new spells out a little too close to a guard.
Guard Highmoon says, &quot;Magicians like you really bring out the worst in me…&quot;</p>

<h3>
Sense Summoned</h3>

<p>
This spell will turn you toward the closest summoned being.&nbsp; It's useful
for finding mobs that are summoned.&nbsp; It can also be used to find mobs that
have pets.&nbsp; For example, if you wish to find an enchanter mob, this spell
might turn you to the enchanter's pet.&nbsp; Note that this spell turns you in
the direction of the mob, not necessarily the direction you'll have to run to
get to that mob.</p>

<p><i>Historical Note: Sense Summoned used to target your pet if it was the
closest summoned being to you.&nbsp; This is no longer the case.&nbsp; Sense
summoned will no longer target your pet.&nbsp; This change greatly increased the
usefulness of Sense Summoned -- although it means you cannot use the spell to
locate a lost pet.</i></p>

<h3>Summoned Items</h3>

<p>
Mages aren't a buffing class. We don't have spells to cast on others to make the
stronger, run faster or be smarter. (I've wished for that last one many times).
Instead, we summon items to give to people. These items are temporary. They
vanish if the player goes offline for more than 30 minutes. At this point, your
ability to summon is fairly limited to mundane items. That will change as you
gain levels. However, even at level 1, you'll save money since you don't have to
buy bandages.&nbsp; Summon Wisp is useful if you're a class that is
night-blind.&nbsp; This spell creates a small light source.</p>

<h3>Summoned Focus Items</h3>

<p>
Focus items are a special type of summoned gear that when worn affects the magic
of the wearer. At this point, you can only summon a Brass Choker. It's a
necklace that when worn, gives you a chance to save your malachite when you cast
a pet summon. The necklace actually works for other classes that have spells
that use components as well (within certain limits). These are high demand items
that were very recently added for magicians. Make use of them!</p>

<h3>Skills</h3>

<p>
You are now able to Mediate! Well, once you train it, that is. Meditate is a
skill that only increases if you train it initially. Just train one point. It
will increase on its own from there. You will automatically meditate when you
sit.</p>

<p><i>
Historical Note: To meditate, players used to have to sit, open the spell book
and click the meditate button. Since casting classes spend a lot of time
meditating, most of us spent a good percentage of time in EQ seeing a spell book
rather than the game graphics. Verant changed the game so that characters level
35+ would automatically meditate when they sat down in the first year of the
game. Today, all casters meditate automatically. So, that's why that useless
meditate button is there under your open spell book!</i></p>

<p>
I would recommend training Alteration and Conjuration at this point. These are
important skills that you may not have used much during your first three levels.
In lieu of training these skills, you can cast Gate to practice alteration. Cast
Summon Food or Drink to practice Conjuration. Don't summon pets to practice your
skill…they cost malachite! To practice, just stand there casting repeatedly.
When you run out of mana, sit and meditate. Repeat.</p>

<p>
You can practice your damage spells this way too. Target yourself and cast. Just
don't kill yourself. This is a safe way to practice Bind Wound. Make bandages,
nuke yourself and fix yourself up. (You can only bandage to 50% of your health).</p>

<p>
Begging is an actual skill in the game. It doesn't have any real use, but if you
wish, you can raise it by begging from your pet. You won't get anything from
your pet…but then, your pet won't decide you need a beating for begging
either. NPCs may not like beggars and may take it upon themselves to teach you a
lesson.&nbsp; I wish I could do that!</p>

<p>
Alcohol tolerance is another skill in the game that's there for fun. You've
worked hard to get to level 4. Stop by the local tavern and celebrate. Oh…and
you're buying.</p>

<p>
Trade skills are useful, although they are expensive pastimes. If you are
interested in taking on trades at this level, I encourage you to read one of the
many fine guides to trade skills. Note that trade skills are very important at
high levels in the game.</p>

<h3>
Melee</h3>

<p>
You should continue to assist your pet with melee.&nbsp; Doing this will not
only help ensure the outcome of the fight, but it will ensure that your offense
and defense skills stay maxed.&nbsp; Offense determines your attack rating (how
often you will hit).&nbsp; Defense is part of your AC calculation.&nbsp; Neither
of these can be trained.&nbsp; The only way to raise them is to melee.</p>
